- Tue 12 Feb 2019. Bunia: a confirmed case of Ebola
[Buniaactualite.com, in French, machine trans., edited]
https://buniaactualite.com/bunia-un-cas-confirme-debola-enregistre-a-la-clinique-salama/

A confirmed case of Ebola haemorrhagic fever was recorded this Mon 11 Feb 2019 in the city of Bunia, capital of Ituri. The interim governor of the province, Pacific Keta, confirmed it to Buniaactualite.com, indicating that it is a woman who died at the Salama clinic and whose samples were not positive after laboratory analysis.

Emergency measures have been taken to prevent new contaminations, ensures the provincial authority.

This is the 1st ever confirmed case of this epidemic in Bunia city since the penetration of the virus in Ituri province in August last year [2018], killing more than 4 people including in Mambasa, Tchomia, and Komanda.

The risk of contamination in the capital of this province had increased since prevention teams along the border with neighboring North Kivu, epicenter of the contagion, have lowered their guard following the non-payment of their taxes.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[See the report regarding this case, which actually originated in Katwa, discussed in the MoH report above. It is unclear why the samples were not positive upon laboratory testing, as stated in this report, possibly because transmission was sexual(?), but the patient was confirmed to have died of Ebola according to the MOH. - Mod.LK]

- Sun 10 Feb 2019. 97 child deaths in DRC
[Save the Children, abridged, edited]
https://www.savethechildren.org/us/about-us/media-and-news/2019-press-releases/ebola-spike-in-democratic-republic-of-congo

Almost 100 children in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) have lost their lives to the Ebola virus since the outbreak started in August last year [2018]. Save the Children warns the death toll could rise as the number of new cases spiked in January [2019], from around 20 a week to more than 40. Of the 97 children who lost their lives, 65 were younger than 5 years old.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

